 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.4","title":"[AA-04.1] Compare wait-free and progress-bounded kernel substrate candidates","description":"Evaluate the queue, wake, and reactor substrate candidates that could reduce kernel tail jitter: wait-free rings, bounded-progress structures, cache-local shards, and other high-EV contenders.","design":"Scope:\\n- Benchmark the current intrusive path against carefully scoped alternatives.\\n- Include implementation complexity, memory cost, determinism impact, and unsafe-surface analysis.\\n- Produce an adoption wedge rather than a theory-only survey.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Candidate matrix includes throughput, p95/p99, allocation, memory footprint, determinism impact, and safety/proof cost.\n2. At least one candidate is selected or explicitly rejected with evidence.\n3. Deterministic unit tests, microbench suites, and workload-smoke E2E entry points exist, and their artifacts are reproducible and tied to AA-01 workloads.\n4. The chosen adoption wedge isolates the new substrate behind a conservative fallback seam and emits structured benchmark logs that explain which candidate won or lost and why.","notes":"Primary risk: chasing a theoretically appealing but practically worse data structure.\\nCountermeasure: comparator-first evaluation on representative workloads.\\nFallback: declare no-regret on the current path if no candidate wins convincingly.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"ubuntu","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:34.279004472Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T18:23:58.675393337Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T18:23:58.675367339Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","scheduler"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:47.869556297Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:34.279004472Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.5","title":"[AA-04.2] Prototype shard-local dispatch, wake, and steal-path redesign behind fallback seam","description":"Implement the selected fast-path experiment for one or more core kernel surfaces such as shard-local dispatch, wake coalescing, steal-path routing, or reactor handoff, always behind a reversible seam.","design":"Scope:\\n- Land a concrete prototype on a narrow surface.\\n- Keep the old path available for direct A/B comparison and rollback.\\n- Preserve determinism, single-owner rules, and structured cleanup semantics.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Prototype path is selectable versus the incumbent path without source divergence.\n2. Benchmarks show measurable wins on at least one important workload family.\n3. Deterministic unit tests and deterministic E2E stress scripts protect ownership, fairness assumptions, no-lost-wakeup behavior, and reversible fallback.\n4. Structured logs show which fast path was active, what workload exercised it, and why fallback engaged if it did.","notes":"Primary risk: correctness regressions hidden behind performance wins.\\nCountermeasure: narrow surface area, explicit toggles, and focused invariants.\\nFallback: old path remains the default until AA-04.3 passes.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"ubuntu","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:39.282075928Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T18:31:27.556866353Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T18:31:27.556834043Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","scheduler"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:39.282075928Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:50.374661113Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.6","title":"[AA-04.3] Run bounded-latency fairness, wakeup, and no-leak regression pack","description":"Explicit validation bead for the fast-path track: stress fairness bounds, wakeup correctness, quiescence, and obligation safety under the new substrate with deterministic workloads and logs.","design":"Scope:\\n- Exercise cancellation storms, steal pressure, wake races, and shutdown.\\n- Measure tail behavior before/after on the AA-01 workload corpus.\\n- Fail closed on fairness or no-leak regressions even if raw throughput improves.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Deterministic unit tests and E2E scenarios cover fairness, wake races, shutdown, and obligation/quiescence invariants.\\n2. Tail tables include p50/p95/p99/p999 deltas versus the incumbent path.\\n3. Structured logs record active substrate, workload ID, fairness counters, and fallback activity.\\n4. Regression verdicts are reproducible and directly linked to rollback commands.","notes":"Primary risk: throughput gains masking tail or safety regressions.\\nCountermeasure: hard fail on invariant or tail-budget regression.\\nFallback: keep the incumbent kernel path as default.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:44.372432449Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:55.464439479Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:55.464380519Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:44.372432449Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:52.910816967Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"asupersync-1508v.5","title":"[AA-05] Static Protocol and Linearity Surface","description":"Move a meaningful slice of obligation correctness and protocol safety from runtime-only enforcement into opt-in compile-time surfaces and deterministic static analyses.","design":"Core idea:\\n- Obligations, permits, leases, and protocol phases are central to Asupersync's identity; the runtime should expose stronger static guarantees where the type system or derived analyses can help.\\n- The goal is not to replace dynamic safety, but to make whole classes of mistakes hard or impossible to write.\\n\\nTrack outputs:\\n- Session/typestate design for obligation-bearing APIs.\\n- Static obligation leak checker prototype.\\n- Graded budget/affine pilot with compile-fail tests and migration guidance.","acceptance_criteria":"1. A clear opt-in static surface exists for at least one important obligation/protocol family.\n2. A deterministic static analysis prototype can flag likely obligation leaks on a restricted but useful subset.\n3. Compile-fail and runtime tests show how the static surface complements, rather than replaces, existing oracles.\n4. Ergonomics and adoption costs are explicitly documented with safe fallback to current dynamic mechanisms.\n5. The track provides deterministic compile-fail, unit, and E2E migration coverage plus structured diagnostics so users can adopt the safer surface without ambiguity.","notes":"Recommendation card:\\n- Change: push no-leak and protocol-discipline guarantees left into compile time.\\n- EV: very high for reliability and long-term maintainability.\\n- Primary risk: ergonomic friction and partial coverage.\\n- Countermeasure: opt-in APIs, macro assistance, and direct comparison against current dynamic oracles.\\n- Conservative fallback: dynamic obligation tracking remains canonical where static coverage is incomplete.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:44:35.108950823Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T06:57:02.322173689Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa05-static-correctness","alien-artifact","correctness","runtime-ascension","types"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:44:35.108950823Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"asupersync-1508v.5","title":"[AA-05] Static Protocol and Linearity Surface","description":"Move a meaningful slice of obligation correctness and protocol safety from runtime-only enforcement into opt-in compile-time surfaces and deterministic static analyses.","design":"Core idea:\\n- Obligations, permits, leases, and protocol phases are central to Asupersync's identity; the runtime should expose stronger static guarantees where the type system or derived analyses can help.\\n- The goal is not to replace dynamic safety, but to make whole classes of mistakes hard or impossible to write.\\n\\nTrack outputs:\\n- Session/typestate design for obligation-bearing APIs.\\n- Static obligation leak checker prototype.\\n- Graded budget/affine pilot with compile-fail tests and migration guidance.","acceptance_criteria":"1. A clear opt-in static surface exists for at least one important obligation/protocol family.\n2. A deterministic static analysis prototype can flag likely obligation leaks on a restricted but useful subset.\n3. Compile-fail and runtime tests show how the static surface complements, rather than replaces, existing oracles.\n4. Ergonomics and adoption costs are explicitly documented with safe fallback to current dynamic mechanisms.\n5. The track provides deterministic compile-fail, unit, and E2E migration coverage plus structured diagnostics so users can adopt the safer surface without ambiguity.","notes":"Recommendation card:\\n- Change: push no-leak and protocol-discipline guarantees left into compile time.\\n- EV: very high for reliability and long-term maintainability.\\n- Primary risk: ergonomic friction and partial coverage.\\n- Countermeasure: opt-in APIs, macro assistance, and direct comparison against current dynamic oracles.\\n- Conservative fallback: dynamic obligation tracking remains canonical where static coverage is incomplete.","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:44:35.108950823Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T18:49:27.193805284Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T18:49:27.193781860Z","close_reason":"All children (AA-05.1, 05.2, 05.3) completed","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa05-static-correctness","alien-artifact","correctness","runtime-ascension","types"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:44:35.108950823Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
